post_text: Nicely done Tullahoma City Schools Nutrition Department!
shared_text:
Tullahoma City Schools Nutrition Department is at Tullahoma High School.
September 10 at 1:20 PM · Tullahoma, TN ·

In the name of health and safety we have been individually portioning ALL our foods. Let me just tell you that it’s hard for a daily VISUAL menu update with lids and foam bowls.... I’m in love with my staff’s ability to adapt and find ways to showcase their hard work! People eat with their eyes and we are really trying to find better ways to deliver the wow factor we have strived so hard to achieve with such unappealing eye challenges! I would say we championed these options today💪🏽 #tcsnutrition

post_text:
On Wednesday, the Tennessee Department of Education opened a new website that displays information on COVID-19 cases by district across the state. When you click the link below, you will see state information first. You can search for Tullahoma City Schools by clicking the search by district option. On the left, you will see the Primary Operating Model for TCS, which is listed as Hybrid-Parent Choice. This Hybrid-Parent Choice means we currently have students engaged in both in-person learning and full distance learning. You will also note if there are less than 5 cases in either student or staff group, it will reflect less than 5. The intent here is to maintain privacy when the numbers are low. If our district reaches a number greater than 5, you will see the actual number. This district dashboard information is updated weekly.
https://districtinformation.tnedu.gov/covid-information/search/-1

post_text: Tullahoma City Schools is excited to announce Bethany McKee as the new Special Education Coordinator. Mrs. McKee holds a Bachelor of Science in Agriculture Communication and a Master’s degree in Early Childhood Special Education both from Auburn University. Mrs. McKee also has an Educational Specialist degree in Principalship from Arkansas State University. She has been educating students since 2012 and has served Tullahoma City Schools for the past four years as a resource teacher at Jack T. Farrar Elementary School and as a 619 preschool dually-certified educator. Her experience with various age groups, experience with early childhood, and her passion for assisting families are evident in her daily interactions with her students, families, and colleagues. These attributes will serve Mrs. McKee well as she takes over the role of Special Education Coordinator. Please help us in welcoming her to this position!

post_text: Mrs. Katie Alderman recently joined Tullahoma City Schools as the Health Science instructor at Tullahoma High School. Mrs. Alderman has an Associate’s degree in Nursing from Bluegrass Community and Technical School and a Bachelor of Science degree in Animal Science from Auburn University. After receiving an R.N. in 2014, she worked in an ICU/ER setting her entire nursing career. She is a certified therapeutic riding instructor and enjoys teaching at Horse Play, Inc. She loves to water ski, snow ski, spend time at the barn, watch football, and read. Mrs. Alderman shares, “I am a proud THS alumni and excited to be back at the high school! I live in Tullahoma with my husband, Stephen, and my two kids, Elaina and Patrick.” Help us in welcoming Mrs. Katie Alderman!

post_text: IMPORTANT! ALL students in ALL schools in our district will be served free breakfast and lunch through December 31, 2020!
shared_text:
USDA.GOV
USDA Extends Free Meals for Kids Through December 31, 2020

Tullahoma City Schools Nutrition Department
September 1 at 5:28 PM ·

#BREAKINGNEWS: USDA extends #schoolmeal #waivers through as late as December 31, 2020, dependent on funding, allowing schools to offer meals to all children 0-18 years old at no charge!!!! This starts immediately at ALL our schools and we are working on a route for #S3 to start next week!

Any families wanting to pick up a week's worth of meals for their children that are NOT CURRENTLY ENROLLED IN TCS call Director of Nutrition- Angela Cardwell at 931-454-2604 to be assigned to a school for weekly pick up's.

All students will enjoy free breakfast and lunch daily at school, or weekly bags will continue for distance learners.

Al a cartes and extras can still be sold to students in the buildings with money on their accounts!

For more information please call 454-2604.

So excited!!!!!
https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2020/08/31/usda-extends-free-meals-kids-through-december-31-2020

post_text: Tullahoma City Schools is excited to welcome Mrs. Caitlin Vaughn to the staff at East Lincoln Elementary. She has a background in intervention at the elementary level and will be teaching 5th-grade intervention at East Lincoln. post_text: We are excited to welcome Olivia Rhoton to Tullahoma City Schools! Mrs. Rhoton will serve as a speech-language pathologist for the district. She has a Bachelor of Science degree in Audiology and Speech Pathology from the University of Tennessee and a Master of Science degree in Speech-Language Pathology from the University of Tennessee Health Science Center. Her time away from work is filled with a love of photography, DIY projects, and time outdoors. She shares, “I am thankful to have the opportunity to work with Tullahoma City Schools. I believe that all students deserve a voice and a means to effectively communicate with their worlds, both academic and social. I look forward to doing my part in the process of achieving this.” Welcome, Olivia Rhoton!

We have added several new teachers throughout the district this school year! In the coming days, we will be sharing many of these exceptional additions to our staff. Let's start with East Middle School's newest team member, Ms. Maggie Ives!

We are excited to welcome Ms. Maggie Ives as the new art teacher at East Middle School. Ms. Ives recently earned a Bachelor of Science degree in Art Education from Middle Tennessee State University. She loves to run, paint, and likes all things funny . . . comedy shows, movies, and talk shows. She shares, “I am so honored to teach your precious children! Art, in the beginning, was always meant to be fun, and I want to bring that fun to this community. I have only been here for a few months, and I already simply love it.” Welcome to Tullahoma City Schools, Maggie Ives!

post_text: The Tullahoma City Schools Board of Education celebrated East Middle School 7th grade student, Joaquin Tenaglia Canut at Tuesday night's meeting. Joaquin has been honored as one of the brightest young students in the world by the Johns Hopkins Center for Talented Youth. Specific testing is used to identify advanced students from around the world. This testing provides a clear picture of their true academic abilities. Joaquin was one of more than 16,000 students from 66 countries who tested in the 2019-2020 talent search. Congratulations to Joaquin and his family! #tcspublic #emspanthers

post_text: Today the active case count in Coffee Coffee reached 285 which puts us at the 0.50% or the moderate spread category. While the number is just at the moderate spread level, schools will remain on regular schedule through Tuesday, August 11 to monitor the case count. Unless there is a change in the trend of increasing active cases, Tullahoma City Schools is announcing a move to its hybrid schedule on Monday, August 17. There will be no school for students Wednesday, August 12 through Friday, August, 14, as teachers prepare for this transition. School staff will be contacting parents with more information. Please be aware that once a change is made the school district will remain on the hybrid schedule for an extended period of time. We will continue to evaluate active case trends to determine when and if change is appropriate within our pathway to re-entry. Ongoing communication will continue through School Messenger, email, the district website and social media platforms. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we respond to the fluid nature of COVID-19.

post_text: Tullahoma City Schools is excited to announce Dr. April Norris as the new Deputy Director of Schools for the district. Dr. Norris has been an educator for over 26 years with the last 7 of those years right here in Tullahoma. She has served Tullahoma City Schools as a special education teacher, principal of Bel-Aire Elementary, and most recently as Director of Special Education. “I am thrilled to announce the appointment of Dr. April Norris as our new Deputy Director of Schools,” Dr. Stephens, Director of Schools, said. “Her educational background and unique experiences will be invaluable, as we serve the students and support the teachers and staff of Tullahoma City Schools.” Norris holds a Doctorate of Education in Educational Leadership from Cumberland University, a Specialist in Education in Instructional Leadership from Tennessee Technological University, a Master of Education in Elementary Education from Tennessee State University, and a Bachelor of Science in special education from Middle Tennessee State University. Help us in welcoming Dr. Norris to this new role!
text: Tullahoma City Schools is excited to announce Dr. April Norris as the new Deputy Director of Schools for the district. Dr. Norris has been an educator for over 26 years with the last 7 of those years right here in Tullahoma. She has served Tullahoma City Schools as a special education teacher, principal of Bel-Aire Elementary, and most recently as Director of Special Education. “I am thrilled to announce the appointment of Dr. April Norris as our new Deputy Director of Schools,” Dr. Stephens, Director of Schools, said. “Her educational background and unique experiences will be invaluable, as we serve the students and support the teachers and staff of Tullahoma City Schools.” Norris holds a Doctorate of Education in Educational Leadership from Cumberland University, a Specialist in Education in Instructional Leadership from Tennessee Technological University, a Master of Education in Elementary Education from Tennessee State University, and a Bachelor of Science in special education from Middle Tennessee State University. Help us in welcoming Dr. Norris to this new role!

post_text: Creating an environment where students feel safe to use failure as a learning opportunity is just one of the keys to success for THS Teacher of the Year, Lisa Lee. Ms. Lee has nineteen years of teaching experience, a Bachelor of Science Degree in Biology, and a Master of Science Degree in Biology. Giving her students clear expectations and paths to success is important in Mr. Lee’s biology and chemistry classes at Tullahoma High School. Her tools of the trade have enabled students to have significant growth in end of course exams, as well as, ACT scores. She shares, “Many of my previous students have contacted me after graduation to tell me how well my class prepared them for college success.” Congratulations to Lisa Lee, THS Teacher of the Year!

post_text: With nearly twenty-five years of teaching experience, Dr. Stevens is in her second year teaching mathematics at Tullahoma High School. Dr. Stevens believes that all students can be successful in math with three things: diligent study, persistence to learn, and an attitude of perseverance. She shares, “A good teacher must realize that students learn at different rates and through different modalities and that one size does not fit all.” We congratulate Dr. Samantha Stevens on being a THS building level, district level, and region level Teacher of the Year recipient!

post_text: Let’s celebrate Ms. Cheryl Lee! With six years of experience in education and a Bachelor of Arts Degree in English Education, she is the West Middle School Teacher of the Year. Ms. Lee loves writing and shares this love with each student that walks into her classroom. She encourages students to write to their best ability by showing her own creative writing and research writing. She shares her strengths and mistakes to help them grow and learn. “We celebrate our mistakes, and students are encouraged to revise their work to demonstrate their growth. Individualized feedback gives them the opportunity to fix and learn from their own mistakes. Podcasts, newspapers, and mock trials show them that writing goes beyond the classroom.” We congratulate Cheryl Lee on being a WMS building level, district level, and region level Teacher of the Year recipient!

post_text: A three-time Teacher of the Year recipient, Mrs. Cindy Middleton currently teaches 3rd grade at East Lincoln Elementary. Bringing instruction to the classroom in a multitude of ways is a focus for Mrs. Middleton. She shares, “I am highly aware of, and constantly attempting to teach to each child’s strengths and individual learning styles.” Congratulations, Cindy Middleton, East Lincoln Elementary’s Teacher of the Year!

post_text: Angie Coop has been an educator for 18 years. With a bachelor’s degree, master’s degree, and Ed.S. in Admin and Supervision, she currently teaches 2nd grade at Jack T. Farrar Elementary. For Ms. Coop, school time is her time to motivate and engage her students. She shares, “My focus is on their opportunities for success at school. I do that by gaining their respect and trust through daily events within our school no matter where we are.” Ms. Coop not only gains the respect of her students but her colleagues as well, and that is why she is the Jack T. Farrar Teacher of the Year!

post_text: With nineteen years of experience in education and a Bachelor’s Degree in Education from Tennessee Tech University, Mrs. Teresa Sebourn teaches 2nd grade at Bel-Aire Elementary. Success in the classroom for Mrs. Sebourn involves many strategies but each year starts by “getting to know my students by learning and observing their interests and ability to express themselves, both orally and in writing.” She has the insight to know that it’s never too early to prepare students for the world. That is why community involvement in her classroom is so important to her. She shares, “During my twenty years of teaching, I have participated in and led many activities and committees that have brought the community into my classroom or took my students into the community.” Preparing young lives for a big world is Bel-Aire Elementary’s Teacher of the Year, Teresa Sebourn! Congratulations, Mrs. Sebourn! #tcspublic #TeacheroftheYear #belairebees

post_text: Katie Hayes is the East Middle School Teacher of the Year. Mrs. Hayes has five years of experience in education and a Bachelor of Science Degree in Education from Tennessee Tech University. Setting the stage for learning is essential for Katie Hayes and she knows the foundation of this is through building great relationships with her students. “I provide a positive climate and culture in my classroom by forming relationships with each student. At the beginning of the year, the students fill out an information sheet which includes their interests, their hobbies, their favorite subject, books they enjoy reading, etc. Then, I use this information to have meaningful conversations with them.” This teacher of the year demands the best out of the students in her classroom all while encouraging and motivating them to achieve not only growth in learning but also in behavior and ethics. There is no doubt why Mrs. Katie Kayes is the East Middle School Teacher of the Year! Congratulations, Mrs. Hayes! #tcspublic #emspanthers #TeacheroftheYear

post_text: Tabitha Sehorne has taught at Robert E. Lee Elementary for nine years. post_text:
Tullahoma City Schools is pleased to announce that Mr. Jason Quick has been selected as the new principal of Tullahoma High School. Jason is a native of Tullahoma and graduated from THS in 1984. He most recently served as an assistant principal and fine arts director of Athens City Schools in Alabama. Mr. Quick has also served as an administrator at Bob Jones High School in Madison, Alabama, teacher and coached at Huntsville High School, Huntsville, Alabama, and the South Gibson Special School District in Tennessee. Please join the Tullahoma City School District in congratulating and welcoming home Jason Quick as Tullahoma High School Principal.

Director Scott Hargrove shares:
“We are very excited about the student-centered approach and positive energy Jason Quick brings to Tullahoma High School. Due to Jason’s familiarity with the high level of expectations and traditions of our high school, we look forward to welcoming back a Wildcat to lead the next steps of success for THS.” #tcspublic #thswildcats #welcome

post_text:
We are excited to announce that Dr. Catherine Stephens will officially begin her role as TCS Director of Schools on June 1st!

Dr. Stephens shares:

"I am thrilled to join Tullahoma City Schools as Superintendent and begin my work on June 1st. I am eager to join in the amazing work happening in the district, where the focus is on students and their total success. It is also rewarding to join a community that takes such pride in its school system that prepares students for their next steps by ensuring college and career readiness.

My husband and I can’t wait to make T-town our home and invest deeply in the community that we are thankful to be joining."

Press Release: April 16, 2020

Tullahoma City Schools will follow the recommendation of Tennessee Governor Bill Lee and close our buildings for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. Distance learning opportunities for our elementary, middle and high school students will continue to be provided through May 15th. Our TCS nutrition team will continue to provide meal pick up through May 22nd. Other services that have been provided during the closure will continue through May 15th.

Please watch our Facebook page as we share further information in the future regarding this closure.

Tullahoma City Schools Nutrition Department
March 18 at 5:43 PM ·

We have been approved an extension to serve grab n go meals through Monday March 23rd!!!!
PLEASE READ THOROUGHLY!
Arrival times may alter on #S3, please be patient and trust we are on our way.
OUR MISSION:
1 Feed our kids.
2 Provide some financial relief for families during shutdown
3 SHUT DOWN food insecurity
4 Limit times away from home
5 Limit redundant work in times of emergency
6 Allow our staff to be able to take care of themselves and their families
7 Be mindful of what foods make sense to serve and be safe
8 Respect the sporadic nature of these ever changing hour by hour mandates & guidelines by finding joy in doing what we love
9 Spread the Love
10 We are better together

***This is new and uncharted territory for not only our world, country, towns,schools and businesses--- but it seems the importance of SCHOOL NUTRITION is truly coming to light in these emergent times.We actively are making changes and trying to make things as easy as possible for not only our students but our staff. #tcsnutrition

post_text:
TCS Statement: March 16, 2020

Tennessee Governor Bill Lee issued a statement earlier today urging Tennessee School districts to close through March 31, 2020. Tullahoma City Schools will extend its closure through the March 31st date recommended by our Governor. Classes are tentatively scheduled to resume on April 1, 2020.

Athletics: March 16, 2020

All Tullahoma City School athletic practices and competitions have been canceled for the week of March 16 - 22, 2020. There will be no athletic competition through March 29, 2020. TCS administration will meet again later in the week to reevaluate the status of next week’s practices. This will include all middle school club sports.

TCS administration will meet again later in the week to reevaluate the status of next week’s practices. This will include all middle school club sports.

post_text: We are excited to announce Dr. Clint Epley as the new principal of Bel-Aire Elementary School! Dr. Epley is a Tullahoma native. He attended Jack T. Farrar Elementary, West Middle School, and is a Tullahoma High School graduate. Dr. Epley has taught 8th-grade social studies at West Middle School and has a Bachelor of Arts degree in History from UT, a Master of Education degree from UT, an Ed.S. from Carson-Newman University, and a Doctorate in Administration and Supervision from Carson-Newman. Dr. Epley shares, "I'm looking forward to building on the great things already taking place at Bel-Aire and am excited to begin forming relationships with the students, faculty, and parents. My family is very happy to be a part of the Bel-Aire community, and I can't wait to get started!" Congratulations, Dr. Epley! #tcspublic #belairebees #welcome

post_text: There will be a new face at the TCS central office on Monday! We are excited to welcome Mr. Jason Ray as the Chief Operations Officer! post_text: TCS cafeteria managers attended the TN School Nutrition Association Annual Conference last week in Gatlinburg. An important part of the week for these managers was ServSafe certification. Each of our cafeteria managers learned about foodborne illnesses, contamination, and food allergens to gain specialized certification through ServSafe. We appreciate these managers always working to do their best for TCS students and staff! #tcspublic #schoolnutrition #ServSafe

post_text: This past weekend, the Tullahoma Archery team competed in the State competition for the outdoor, 3-D season. Two TCS students finished in the top 3! post_text: We are excited to announce Mr. Bryan Morris as the new head coach of the Tullahoma High School baseball team! A 2005 THS grad, Coach Morris was the Tennessee Louisville Slugger player of the year, Tennessee Pro Line player of the year, and Tennessee Gatorade player of the year during his time at THS. He spent a year at Motlow State Community College and was then drafted in the first round of the 2006 draft by the L.A. Dodgers. Coach Morris spent 6 years in the minor leagues and made his major league debut in September of 2012 with the Pittsburgh Pirates. He spent 12 years playing professional baseball. Coach Morris and his wife, Chelsey, have been married 10 years and have two children. Coach Morris shares that he and his family are "thrilled to be back home and are looking forward to being a part of Tullahoma's historic baseball program." Welcome back to the Wildcat Nation, Coach Morris! #tcspublic #thswildcats #wildcatsbaseball

post_text:
Tullahoma City Schools (TCS) welcomes applicants for a Human Resources Specialist position at Tullahoma City Schools. This year-round position serves as the assistant to the director of Human Resources and will be a vital role for the school system. Individuals with a background in Human Resources are encouraged to apply. Interested persons may apply online at www.tcsedu.net, under the Human Resources tab. We will review all active applicants and notify those selected for interview opportunities. Equal employment opportunity and treatment shall be practiced by TCS regardless of race, color, national origin, religion, sex, age, marital status and disability if the employee, with or without reasonable accommodation, is able to perform the essential functions of the position. In accordance with Tennessee statute, TCS is an at-will employer.
http://bit.ly/TCSHRAssistant

post_text: Julie Koster is the 2019 East Middle School Teacher of the Year! Mrs. Koster teaches 8th grade ELA and has a Bachelor of Science degree and a master’s degree from State University of New York at Oneonta. “In my classroom, I spend time at the beginning of the year getting to know my students and helping them set goals for the year. By knowing who my students are as people, I can help them become the best they can be as learners.” Instruction in Mrs. Koster’s class is the result of researching, planning, and creating lessons that will engage every learner. Congratulations, Julie Koster, East Middle School Teacher of the Year! #tcspublic #emspanthers

post_text: Mr. Randy Edwards is not only a 2019 THS Teacher of the Year, but also a District Level Teacher of the Year! Mr. Edwards teaches Architectural and Engineering Design at Tullahoma High School. He has a Bachelor of Science degree from Middle Tennessee State University. Mr. Edwards believes that a critical tool for his classroom success has been to utilize former students as mentors to current students. This technique provides individual instruction as well as encouragement for future education and employment opportunities. Mr. Edwards has also been an integral part of building and renovation design projects at THS. From a soccer press box, to football concession stands, to redesigning the THS attendance office, Mr. Edwards offered his students the opportunity to be involved in the development, planning and completion of these projects. Congratulations, Mr. Edwards, on being the 2019 THS and District Level Teacher of the Year! #tcspublic #thswildcats

post_text: Congratulations to Charlie Hickerson, 2019 THS Teacher of the Year! Mr. Hickerson teaches English IV and AP English Literature at THS and has a Bachelor of Science degree from Middle Tennessee State University. Mr. Hickerson shares, “In all my years as an English teacher, I have strived to make English literature as accessible and ‘non-threatening’ as possible. “ In addition to teaching at THS, Mr. Hickerson has also headed and organized a fund-raiser for Project Graduation called “Rock Graduation”. This fund-raiser encouraged high school rock bands to perform in a non-competitive environment while also raising funds for Project Graduation. THS is proud to call Mr. Charlie Hickerson a Teacher of the Year! #tcspublic #thswildcats

post_text:
There's a lot of buzz about Makerspace! But what in the world is Makerspace, you might ask. Makerspace activities allow students to tinker, build, or even take apart different objects or components. Students learn to explore, collaborate, and share giving way to improved imagination, improved critical thinking skills, and improved problem solving skills.

Students in Mrs. Gluch's 1st-grade class at Jack T. Farrar Elementary created Leprechaun traps during Makerspace time yesterday! #tcspublic #jtffrogs #funwaystolearn #imagine #create #dream #STEM

post_text: Ashley Gass is the 2019 Robert E. Lee Elementary Teacher of the Year! Mrs. Gass has a Bachelor of Science degree in Special Education from Tennessee Tech University. Mrs. Gass shares, “For my students to reach their full potential, it is my responsibility to provide a safe environment through establishing trust by building on their strengths and interests to improve areas of weakness.” In 2017, Mrs. Gass created a group called the Legendary Lion Leaders. This group provides peer mentoring that supports students with special needs. The mission of this group is to Lead, Include, Optimize, and Nurture by building and establishing friendships, encouraging positive, meaningful interactions, and providing opportunities to include all individuals. Congratulations to Mrs. Ashley Gass, the 2019 Robert E. Lee Elementary Teacher of the Year! #tcspublic #RELlions

post_text: Congratulations to THS Teacher of the Year, Keith Gilliam! Mr. Gilliam has taught machining at THS for 34 years and holds a bachelor’s degree from Middle Tennessee State University. Mr. Gilliam uses his expertise in operating milling machines, CNC lathes, and CNC mills to give students the skills they need to be career ready. Students in his classes have had the opportunity to compete in the Moon Buggy National Competition. Students have gained employment at Red Stone Arsenal in Huntsville due to the success of the Moon Buggy program. THS is proud to have Mr. Keith Gilliam as a THS Teacher of the Year!

post_text: Students in Ms. Cantrell's art classes at Jack T. Farrar Elementary have been making winter tree resists. A resist is an art technique that uses layers to define a design. A resist layer shapes the invisible design, then the artist paints over surrounding areas to expose the resist layer. The result for these JTF arts students? Beautiful winter scenes with trees and snowflakes! #tcspublic #jtffrogs #winterart #tcsfinearts

post_text: The warm weather this week has allowed teachers to get students out of the buildings for outdoor instruction. Mrs. Harris's class at West Middle School enjoyed using their Walking Classroom program yesterday. The Walking Classroom incorporates podcasts of various educational topics along with physical activity. Each podcast is about 15 minutes in length and comes with additional resources for teachers to lead follow up class discussions. Thanks to a community grant and a matching grant from the Walking Classroom, TCS students have an opportunity to use this program in or out of the classroom. #tcspublic #coordinatedschoolhealth #walkingclassroom #wmsbobcats

post_text: Folklore says if you open a persimmon seed, the shape inside indicates what kind of winter is to come. A fork means the winter will be mild, a spoon means there will be a lot of snow, and a knife means it will be really cold. Inquiring minds in Mrs. Cashion's 7th-grade class at West Middle School decided to test this folklore. Today they opened a seed and discovered a spoon inside! Will the persimmon experiment hold true? We'll just have to wait and see! #tcspublic
